# Cyrius — Core Reference
# Overview, syntax, compiler architecture, dev loop, current limitations,
# porting guide, stdlib catalog.
# 7 entries.

[[entries]]
name = "overview"
description = "What Cyrius is — sovereign self-hosting systems language. Assembly up."
category = "cyrius"
---
Cyrius is a self-hosting compiler that bootstraps from a 29 KB
binary seed. No Rust, no LLVM, no Python. Just sh + Linux.

Default integer type is i64. Multi-width types via annotation:
`var x: i8 = 42;` `var y: i16 = 1000;` `var z: i32 = 0;` produce
width-correct loads (movzx) and stores. `sizeof(Type)` operator.
Type annotations enable width-correct codegen; untyped variables
remain i64. f64 supported as bit patterns via 28+ f64_* builtins
(SSE2/SSE4.1/x87 + 10 SIMD packed-double primitives via
SSE2 / NEON `.2D` — `f64v_add/sub/mul/div/sqrt/abs/fmadd`
since v1.9.0, `f64v_dot/scale/axpy` added at v5.10.17 for
hisab gap-close).

THE COMPILER BINARY:
- `cycc` is the current generation (renamed from cc3 at v5.0.0,
  renamed to `cycc` at v6.0.0 — the FINAL binary name forever
  per the "Version lives in `VERSION` + `--version`, never in
  binary names" rule).
- Self-hosts byte-identical (two-step + three-step verify).
- Cross-compiles to aarch64 via `src/main_aarch64.cyr`.
- Apple Silicon Mach-O self-hosts byte-identically.
- Windows PE32+ self-hosts natively byte-identical (`cycc_win.exe`
  on Windows 11 produces output matching Linux cross-build
  byte-for-byte).
- 11 modules (frontend/lex + frontend/parse + frontend/ts/* +
  backend/x86/* + backend/aarch64/* + backend/cx + backend/macho
  + backend/pe + backend/js + common/ir + cc compatibility layer).

BUILD / COMPILE / TEST:
- Bootstrap:   `sh bootstrap/bootstrap.sh` (~40ms)
- Compile:     `cyrius build src/main.cyr build/myapp`
                (auto-resolves deps from cyrius.cyml)
- Test:        `cyrius test src/test.cyr`
- Audit:       `sh scripts/check.sh` (self-host + heap + tcyr
                + fmt + lint)
- Version:     `cycc --version`

OPTIONAL COMPILER MODES:
- `cycc --strict` — undefined-fn warnings become hard errors (CI).
- Regalloc: default-ON since v5.6.24. Every x86 fn (no inline asm
  in body) gets Poletto-Sarkar linear-scan picker pinning up to 5
  hot locals to rbx/r12-r15. Override via env: CYRIUS_REGALLOC_AUTO_CAP=0
  (disable) or =N (cap at first N fns, bisection).
- IR pipeline: CYRIUS_IR=1 records IR + emits x86; CYRIUS_IR=3
  also runs the optimization passes (LASE + const-fold + bitmap
  liveness DCE + DSE + fixed-point driver).
- Profiling: CYRIUS_PROF=1 (clock_gettime wall-clock; cross-platform
  via __got on Mach-O / kernel32 on PE).

IMPORTANT — use `cyrius build` not raw `cat file | cycc` for projects:
`cyrius build` resolves deps from `cyrius.cyml` and auto-prepends
includes. Raw cycc misses namespaced deps (lib/{depname}_{basename})
and produces undefined-variable errors. Raw cycc is only correct
for: compiler self-hosting, one-liner tests, the bootstrap chain.

LANGUAGE FEATURES SHIPPED (not exhaustive):
- Multi-width types (i8/i16/i32/i64/u128), sizeof, unions,
  bitfield builtins, defer (all exit paths, per-flag).
- Struct field widths, expression type propagation, narrowing
  warnings. Struct initializer syntax, native multi-return,
  short-circuit && / ||, expression-position comparisons.
- Slices: `slice<T>` / `[T]` first-class type with bounds-aware
  `s[i]` indexing and `s.ptr` / `s.len` dot-syntax field access.
- Compound assignment (+=, -=, *=, %=, etc.), negative literals.
- `#regalloc` directive (per-fn opt-in).
- `#ifplat PLAT` / `#endplat` (sugar for `#ifdef CYRIUS_ARCH_*`).
- `#pe_import("kernel32.dll", "Symbol")` (PE IAT registration).
- `#derive(accessors / Serialize)` with single-pass JSON
  deserializer.
- `secret var` (constant-time comparison helper for sigil PQC).
- Per-arch asm dispatch via `#ifdef CYRIUS_ARCH_{X86,AARCH64}`;
  new consumers should prefer `#ifplat` syntax.
- Inline small fns (token replay).
- PIC codegen for `object;` mode (LEA + R_X86_64_PC32, no
  DT_TEXTREL — glibc 2.38+ dlopen-safe).
- `_cyrius_init` export wraps top-level code as a callable
  function in `object;` mode.
- TS/TSX → JS emitter: `cycc --emit-js file.tsx` (+ `cyrius build
  --target=js`) — type-strips + lowers JSX to `h(...)`, emits
  runnable JS (v6.1.11/.12; `backend/js`).
- Numeric preprocessor: `#if NAME >= VALUE` (`== != < > <= >=`)
  over `#define NAME VALUE` ints (v5.6.x; e.g. sakshi `SAKSHI_LEVEL`).
- PIE codegen: `--pie` / `CYRIUS_PIE=1` → ET_DYN position-
  independent executables (x86_64 v6.1.6 + aarch64 v6.1.8).
- `.gnu.hash` dynamic linking for shared objects (v6.1.9; drops the
  legacy SysV `.hash`).
- Windows directory listing: `dir_list` / `is_dir` / `dir_walk`
  route to FindFirstFileW on PE (v6.1.18; `lib/fs_win.cyr`) —
  completing the Windows file surface (process / thread / TLS / env
  / file-I/O / directory-enumeration, v6.1.16–.18).

OPTIMIZATIONS LANDED:
- Constant folding (parse-time + IR-level).
- Tail-call optimization.
- DCE (bitmap O(T+N) for unreachable fns; bitmap-liveness in IR).
- Jump tables (dense switches).
- Dead-store elimination.
- Return-by-value small structs (ret2/rethi).

[[entries]]
name = "syntax"
description = "Complete Cyrius language syntax reference"
category = "cyrius"
---
VARIABLES:
    var x = 42;            # scalar (8 bytes)
    var x: i64 = 42;       # with type annotation
    var slots: i64[256];   # element-typed array — 256 i64 SLOTS (2048 B) [v6.2.1]
    var buf[256];          # bare array — N BYTES in a fn, N i64 slots at top level
    x = x + 1;             # reassignment

FUNCTIONS:
    fn add(a, b) { return a + b; }
    var r = add(20, 22);
    # Up to 6 register params, 7+ on stack
    # Forward calls work (call functions defined later)

CONTROL FLOW:
    if (x == 1) { ... } elif (x == 2) { ... } else { ... }
    while (cond) { ... }
    for (var i = 0; i < 10; i = i + 1) { ... }
    break;    # exit loop
    continue; # skip to next iteration

OPERATORS:
    + - * / %              # arithmetic
    == != < > <= >=        # comparison
    & | ^ ~ << >>          # bitwise
    && ||                  # logical (short-circuit, chainable)
    += -= *= /= %= &= |= ^= <<= >>=   # compound assignment

OVERFLOW-EXPLICIT (lib/overflow.cyr):
    +% -% *%               # wrapping
    +| -| *|               # saturating
    +? -? *?               # checked (panic on overflow)

MEMORY:
    store8(&buf, 65);  load8(&buf);     # byte
    store16/32/64      load16/32/64     # 16/32/64-bit

POINTERS:
    var p = &x;        # address-of
    var v = *p;        # dereference
    *p = 99;           # write through pointer
    var p: *i64 = &buf; *(p + 1);  # typed (scales by element size)

STRUCTS:
    struct Point { x; y; }
    var p = Point { 10, 20 };
    p.x = 42;
    struct Rect { tl: Point; br: Point; }  # nested
    var r = Rect { 0, 0, 10, 5 };
    r.br.x;  # chained dot access

SLICES:
    var s: [u8] = 0;            # or: var s: slice<u8> = 0;
    slice_set(&s, &buf, 5);
    var b = s[0];               # bounds-checked u8 load
    var p = s.ptr;              # field access
    var n = s.len;

STRINGS:
    "hello\n"  # null-terminated; UTF-8 bytes pass through verbatim
    # Escapes: \n \r \t \0 \\ \" \' \a \b \f \v
    #          \x##         (1 byte, two hex digits)
    #          \u####       (UTF-8 codepoint, 4 hex digits)
    #          \u{1..6 hex} (UTF-8 codepoint, up to U+10FFFF)
    #          surrogates D800-DFFF rejected at lex time
    syscall(1, 1, "hello", 5);
    syscall(1, 1, "\x1b[?1049h", 8);   # ANSI alt-screen
    var grin = "\u{1F600}";              # 4 UTF-8 bytes

SYSCALLS:
    syscall(1, 1, buf, len);   # write
    syscall(0, 0, buf, len);   # read
    syscall(60, code);         # exit

INCLUDES:
    include "lib/string.cyr"   # textual inclusion (relative to cwd)

INLINE ASM:
    asm { 0x90; }              # raw bytes
    asm { cli; sti; hlt; }     # mnemonics
    asm { mov cr3, rax; }      # privileged
    asm { lgdt [rax]; }        # descriptor tables

KERNEL MODE:
    kernel;                    # emit bare-metal multiboot1 ELF

OBJECT MODE:
    object;                    # emit ELF .o relocatable (PIC)

[[entries]]
name = "compiler_architecture"
description = "How the cycc compiler is structured: modules, passes, layout (high-level)"
category = "cyrius"
---
MODULES (included by src/main.cyr):
    common/util.cyr  — state accessors, helpers
    common/ir.cyr    — IR opcode definitions and walker
    backend/x86/*    — x86_64 emit, jump, fixup
    backend/aarch64/*— AArch64 emit, jump, fixup
    backend/macho/*  — Mach-O object/exec emission
    backend/pe/*     — Windows PE/COFF emission
    backend/cx/*     — cyrius-x bytecode backend
    frontend/lex.cyr — tokenizer
    frontend/parse/* — parser + codegen (split: types/expr/decl/ctrl/fn)
    frontend/ts/*    — TypeScript-syntax accept layer

COMPILATION FLOW:
    1. Read source (stdin or file) into input buffer
    2. PREPROCESS: expand include directives, ifdef, derive, macros
    3. LEX: tokenize into tok_types/tok_values arrays
    4. Pass 1: scan struct/fn/var declarations (register names,
       skip fn bodies)
    5. Pass 2: parse fn bodies (all globals already registered)
    6. Emit jmp over fn bodies → parse fn defs → patch jmp
    7. EMIT_GVAR_INITS: replay deferred global var initializations
    8. PARSE_PROG: parse main code statements
    9. FIXUP: patch variable / string / function addresses
    10. EMITELF: write ELF binary to stdout (or .o, or PE, or Mach-O)

CODEGEN MODEL:
    - Expression evaluation: first nesting uses R12 spill, deeper
      levels push/pop
    - rax = result register, rcx = scratch, r12 = first spill register
    - Prologue: push rbx; push r12; push rbp; mov rbp, rsp
                (stack params at +32)
    - Epilogue: leave; pop r12; pop rbx; ret
    - Variables at fixed addresses in data section
      (EVLOAD/EVSTORE + fixup)
    - Function calls via rel32 fixup (type 2)
    - String addresses via abs64 fixup (type 1)

OPTIMIZATION PIPELINE (CYRIUS_IR=3):
    - apply_lase (load-after-store elimination)
    - ir_const_fold (constant folding at IR level)
    - ir_dce (dead-code elimination via bitmap liveness)
    - DSE (dead-store elimination)
    - Fixed-point driver (re-runs passes until no further changes)

HEAP REGIONS ARE FIXED — NOT MMAP'D ON DEMAND. cycc reserves a
multi-MB heap at brk; every region (preprocess_out, codebuf,
tok_*, fn_*, etc.) is at a hardcoded offset within it. There's
no allocator at the compiler level. If a project crosses a cap
(preprocessor output, codebuf, output_buf, fn table), the
compile errors out with a clear message and a tip.

[[entries]]
name = "development_loop"
description = "The proven development process for adding features to a Cyrius project"
category = "cyrius"
---
1. RESEARCH  — Check vidya for existing patterns. If covered, skip to 3.
2. VIDYA     — Document patterns, gotchas, codegen BEFORE coding.
3. BUILD     — ONE change at a time. Before compiling, check:
               - Duplicate var scan (no var x in two branches of same fn)
               - Brace balance
               - Bridge compiler supports syntax used in source
               - Heap offset map (no collisions if compiler-level work)
4. TEST      — After EACH change:
               - Basic: `echo 'var x = 42;' | ./build/cycc > t && chmod +x t && ./t`
               - Feature-specific test
               - Self-hosting: cycc==cc5b byte-identical (compiler work only)
               - Full suite only after basic passes
5. IF BROKEN — Revert to last known good. Apply ONE change. Test. Repeat.
               If 3 attempts fail: defer, document root cause, ASK USER.
6. AUDIT     — Full chain: bootstrap, all suites, self-hosting (compiler).
7. VIDYA+DOCS — Document findings. Update CHANGELOG, roadmap, benchmarks.
8. ALIGN     — After major events: sync ALL docs to current state.
               README, CLAUDE.md, roadmap, architecture docs, CHANGELOG.

KEY LESSONS:
- Programs are the best compiler fuzzers — build real things early
- Bridge compiler determines what syntax source files can use
- Test after EVERY change, not after the feature is "done"
- Capacity expansions (codebuf, tokens, input) must be separate commits

[[entries]]
name = "known_limitations"
description = "Current Cyrius language limitations and gotchas you'll hit"
category = "cyrius"
---
CURRENT LIMITATIONS (active — work around these):

1. MIXED &&/|| REQUIRES EXPLICIT PARENS: `a > 0 && b > 0 || c > 0`
   fails to parse — no precedence-based disambiguation. Write
   `a > 0 && (b > 0 || c > 0)` or `(a > 0 && b > 0) || c > 0`
   instead. All parenthesized forms work.

2. NO `i++` / `++i`: Increment/decrement operators aren't in the
   grammar. Use `i += 1` or `i = i + 1`. FOR-loop step accepts any
   assignment expression: `for (var i = 0; i < n; i += 1)`.

3. EXIT CODE TRUNCATION: Linux exit codes wrap at 256. Use
   print_num for values > 255.

4. INLINE ASM REGISTER STATE: asm blocks operate on the register
   state at that point. The compiler may have values in rax/rcx.
   Use push/pop to save state if needed. CAUTION: `[rbp-N]`
   offsets depend on param count and local index — count
   carefully and match against PARSE_FN_DEF's (idx+1)*8 formula.
   `#regalloc` fns shift locals by an extra -8 to reserve [rbp-8]
   for the saved rbx; asm blocks inside them must compensate or
   disable routing.

5. NO CLOSURES CAPTURING VARIABLES: Pure fn pointers only —
   `&fn_name` works (fncall0–fncall8 from fnptr.cyr), but
   lexical capture does not. Use named functions + globals for
   shared state.

6. LARGE `var buf[N]` EXHAUSTS OUTPUT BUFFER: Anything over ~4 KB
   in binary data should be alloc()'d at runtime, not declared as
   `var buf[N]` (which writes N zeros into the ELF). Use
   `var buf = 0; fn init() { buf = alloc(N); }`.

7. ENUM INIT ORDERING: Enum init runs BEFORE gvar init in
   main.cyr. If you modify the compiler, do NOT reorder these —
   gvar init may call functions that reference enum values.

8. BARE `var buf[N]` IS BYTES (in a fn): a function-local `var buf[N]`
   allocates N BYTES, not N i64 elements. `var buf[8]` = 8 bytes (1 i64).
   `var buf[120]` = 120 bytes (15 i64s). At TOP level the same `var buf[N]`
   is N i64 SLOTS (N*8). Easy mistake — bit repeatedly (incl. a daimon
   route-404 from `store64(&parts + i*8)` into a local `var parts[4]`).
   FIX (v6.2.1): for slot arrays use the explicit element-typed form
   `var a: i64[N]` (= N i64 slots = N*8 bytes, SAME in fn + top level);
   `var a: u8[N]` for an explicit byte buffer; widths i8..i64/u8..u64,
   u128. The element width is registered into the 0x12A000 var-size
   table so every backend (x86/aarch64/macho/pe/cx) inherits it — pure
   frontend change. See CHANGELOG [6.2.1].

9. ~~`var x: u128` AT FN SCOPE~~ — RESOLVED at v5.8.16 §8.
   Pre-v5.8.16, scalar_type=16 fn-locals only reserved one 8-byte
   slot; two adjacent slice/u128 fn-locals silently shared a slot
   and `&x + 8` overflowed into saved-rbp territory. v5.8.16
   layout-flip allocates BOTH slots with the canonical (named)
   slot at the LOWER stack address so `&x + 8` correctly
   addresses the high half. `var x: u128 = 0;` is now fully
   load-bearing. The pre-v5.8.16 workaround (`var buf[16]; pass
   as pointer`) still works but is no longer needed. Same fix
   covers fn-local slices — see features.cyml's slice_type_v58x
   entry.

10. INCLUDE IN KERNEL MODE: Not supported. `kernel;` mode blocks
    require single-file source or external concatenation.

11. PREPROCESSOR OUTPUT CAP: Expanded source hard-capped (current
    cap surfaces as a clear error message). The right fix is
    almost always to grow the cap, not trim the program.

12. ELF / OBJECT OUTPUT CAP: Generated binary hard-capped via
    `EMITELF_USER` / `EMITELF_SHARED` / `EMITELF_OBJ` filesz
    checks. Same grow-the-cap rule applies.

13. CODEBUF CAP: Generated machine code hard-capped. If a future
    consumer crosses this, it gets the standard heap-reshuffle
    treatment.

14. CYRIUS `/` AND `%` ARE SIGNED: The `/` operator lowers to
    `idiv`, not `div`. For u64 operations where the top bit is
    meaningful (cryptographic mulmod, hashing, high-entropy
    counters), prefer the stdlib's `u64_mulmod` / `u64_powmod`
    / `u128_divmod` — they handle unsigned semantics internally.

GOTCHAS (expected behavior, not bugs):

15. DYNAMIC LOOP BOUNDS: `for (var i = 0; i < GLOBAL; i = i + 1)`
    re-evaluates GLOBAL each iteration. If the loop body modifies
    GLOBAL, the loop count changes dynamically. FIX: snapshot to
    a local first.

16. OPERATOR OVERLOADING + ALLOC: `Type_add(a, b)` works for value
    types. For pointer-based types (Str), the function receives
    the pointer value. For stack-allocated structs (Point), it
    receives the first field value.

17. SUB-µs BENCHMARKS: `bench_start`/`end` has ~120ns
    clock_gettime overhead + 6ns fncall dispatch. For operations
    under 1µs, use `bench_batch_start` / `bench_batch_stop` with
    `batch_size >= 1000`.

18. OBJECT-MODE GLOBALS: In `object;` mode, top-level code (enum
    values, global var inits) is wrapped in a callable
    `_cyrius_init()` function. C launchers MUST call
    `_cyrius_init()` before `alloc_init()` before any application
    function, or enum-value globals will be zero.

[[entries]]
name = "porting_guide"
description = "How to port Cyrius to a new architecture (aarch64 example)"
category = "cyrius"
---
The compiler is factored into arch-independent frontend and
arch-specific backend.

FRONTEND (shared, no changes needed):
    common/util.cyr     — state accessors
    common/ir.cyr       — IR opcodes
    frontend/lex.cyr    — tokenizer
    frontend/parse/*    — parser (calls emit/jump functions by name)
    src/main.cyr        — main loop

BACKEND (per-architecture):
    backend/<ARCH>/emit.cyr    — instruction emission (~50 functions)
    backend/<ARCH>/jump.cyr    — branch/patch (~4 functions)
    backend/<ARCH>/fixup.cyr   — address patching + ELF emission

TO PORT:
1. Create `backend/<ARCH>/emit.cyr` with same function signatures
   as x86_64
2. Create `backend/<ARCH>/jump.cyr` — branch encoding differs per
   arch
3. Create `backend/<ARCH>/fixup.cyr` — ELF header + address
   patching
4. Create `src/main_<ARCH>.cyr` that includes the new backend
   instead of x86_64
5. Build cross-compiler: `cat src/main_<ARCH>.cyr | ./build/cycc
   > build/cycc_<ARCH>`

KEY MAPPINGS (x86_64 → aarch64 example):
    EMOVI(imm64)  → MOVZ/MOVK sequence (up to 4 instructions)
    EPUSHR/EPOPR  → STR/LDR with SP pre/post-index
    EADDR/ESUBR   → ADD/SUB register-register
    EIMUL/EIDIV   → MUL/SDIV
    ELODC/ESTOC   → LDR/STR [x1]
    ESYSCALL      → SVC #0 (x8=syscall number, x0-x5=args)
    EJCC(cc)      → B.cond (map x86 cc to ARM condition codes)
    EJMP/EJMP0    → B imm26
    FIXUP var     → patch MOVZ/MOVK immediate fields
    FIXUP fn call → patch BL offset

TESTING:
    qemu-system-aarch64 for kernel; qemu-aarch64 for userspace
    (Linux); native aarch64 hardware (Pi 4) for direct verify.

[[entries]]
name = "stdlib"
description = "Cyrius standard library catalog — modules, key APIs, dep bundles"
category = "cyrius"
---
CORE LIBRARIES (lib/) — first-party stdlib modules + per-arch/OS
variants + dep bundles. All ship in the toolchain.

string.cyr      — strlen, streq, memeq, memcpy, memset, memchr, strchr, strstr, print_num, println
alloc.cyr       — alloc_init, alloc, alloc_reset, alloc_used (bump from brk; routes to alloc_macos.cyr mmap on macOS, alloc_windows.cyr VirtualAlloc on Windows)
str.cyr         — Str struct (data+len): str_from, str_len, str_eq, str_cat, str_sub, str_contains, str_split, str_trim
vec.cyr         — Dynamic array: vec_new, vec_push, vec_pop, vec_get, vec_set, vec_len, vec_find, vec_remove
io.cyr          — File I/O: file_open, file_read, file_write, file_close, file_read_all, file_write_all, file_exists, plus flock(2) wrappers (file_lock, file_trylock, file_lock_shared, file_append_locked)
fmt.cyr         — Formatting: fmt_int, fmt_hex, fmt_hex0x, fmt_bool, fmt_byte, fmt_pad, fmt_int_buf, sprintf, fmt_float
args.cyr        — CLI args: args_init, argc, argv (Linux: /proc/self/cmdline)
fnptr.cyr       — Function pointers: fncall0–fncall8 (see "fncall_ceiling" entry for ABI rules)
tagged.cyr      — Tagged unions: packed Result (Ok/Err via bit 63), heap Option (Some/None)
hashmap.cyr     — map_new (cstr keys) + map_new_str (Str keys, content-hashed) + map_u64_new (u64 keys, SplitMix64, zero-alloc hot path)
fs.cyr          — Filesystem: is_dir, dir_list, sys_mkdir, sys_unlink, sys_chmod
process.cyr     — Subprocess: run, run_capture, spawn, exec_vec, exec_env, exec_capture
syscalls.cyr    — Per-arch dispatch (x86_64_linux, aarch64_linux, macos, windows)
net.cyr         — TCP socket wrappers
http.cyr        — HTTP/1.0 client (GET, URL parser, response extraction; CRLF-injection hardened)
http_server.cyr — Minimal HTTP/1.0 server (used by `vidya serve`, `cyrius doc --serve`)
ws.cyr          — WebSocket client (RFC 6455 — handshake, framing, masking, ping/pong)
ws_server.cyr   — WebSocket server
tls.cyr         — TLS 1.3 client (RFC 8446; libssl.so.3 via dynlib bridge). Pair with fdlopen.cyr.
bayan.cyr       — Data formats + big-int (carved from stdlib v6.1.25): json (bayan_json_parse/get/get_int/build/v_pointer RFC 6901 + pretty/streaming), toml, cyml (TOML header + markdown body), csv (RFC 4180), base64, bigint (256-bit u256, 4-limb), u128 (hardware fast-path, ~12× Miller-Rabin). Legacy aliases kept. include "lib/bayan.cyr".
math.cyr        — Math primitives (F64 constants, basic ops, gcd/lcm, f64_parse, f64-builtin polyfills). Advanced/transcendental math carved to ganita.cyr at v6.1.26.
ganita.cyr      — Linear algebra + advanced math (carved from stdlib v6.1.26): matrix (ganita_mat_*), linalg (LU/det/inv/Cholesky/QR/least-squares/eigen/SVD), transcendentals + fibonacci/binomial. Legacy aliases kept. include "lib/ganita.cyr".
regex.cyr       — Pattern matching
trait.cyr       — Manual vtable dispatch
assert.cyr      — Test assertions: assert_eq, assert_ne, assert, assert_summary, test_group
bench.cyr       — Benchmarking: bench_start/end/report + bench_batch_start/stop (sub-µs)
bounds.cyr      — Array bounds checking
callback.cyr    — Callback patterns: fork_with_pre_exec
thread.cyr      — Threads (clone+mmap), mutex (futex), MPSC channels
async.cyr       — Async primitives
freelist.cyr    — Freelist allocator (O(1) alloc/free)
chrono.cyr      — Time: ISO-8601 format/parse, epoch↔date, leap year, sleep_ms, monotonic clocks
log.cyr         — Structured logging wrapper over sakshi (ISO-8601 timestamps, level filtering)
audio.cyr       — ALSA PCM audio via direct ioctls (no libasound, no C FFI)
mmap.cyr        — Memory-mapped I/O: cyr_mmap, cyr_munmap, cyr_mprotect, mmap_file_ro/rw/anon
dynlib.cyr      — Pure-cyrius ELF .so loader via mmap (GNU hash table, no libc, no dlopen)
keccak.cyr      — Keccak-f[1600] + SHAKE-128/256 (NIST-verified)
sha1.cyr        — SHA-1 (NIST FIPS 180-4 vectors)
ct.cyr          — Constant-time primitives backing `secret var` (sigil PQC helper)
cffi.cyr        — C FFI shim surface (struct-by-value / variadic / >6-arg helpers; see docs/ffi/)
fdlopen.cyr     — Foreign-dlopen primitives (x86_64 Linux). Required by lib/tls.cyr.
overflow.cyr    — Saturating + checked arithmetic helpers (+|, -|, *|, +?, -?, *?)
random.cyr      — Kernel-entropy reader
security.cyr    — Landlock policy enums
test.cyr        — Table-driven test framework (test_each)
sandhi.cyr      — Service-boundary stdlib (HTTP/TLS/discovery)
vidya.cyr       — Vidya knowledge-base access

IDENTITY (NSS-free quartet — musl-pattern /etc/* readers, bypass glibc NSS):
pwd.cyr         — pwd_getpwuid / pwd_getpwnam
grp.cyr         — grp_getgrgid / grp_getgrnam / grp_getgrouplist
shadow.cyr      — shadow_getspnam (root-only)
pam.cyr         — pam_unix_authenticate (forks /usr/sbin/unix_chkpwd for non-root)

PER-ARCH / PER-OS VARIANTS (auto-selected via _TARGET_* predefines):
syscalls_x86_64_linux.cyr / syscalls_aarch64_linux.cyr
syscalls_macos.cyr / syscalls_windows.cyr
alloc_macos.cyr (mmap) / alloc_windows.cyr (VirtualAlloc)
args_macos.cyr (x28 entry-prologue argc/argv reader)

DEP BUNDLES (fetched via `cyrius deps` from cyrius.cyml):
sakshi   — Tracing/logging (slim + full profiles)
patra    — SQL database (B-tree, WAL, transactions; bundle via `cyrius distlib`)
sigil    — Ed25519, SHA-256/512, HMAC, HKDF, SHAKE-128/256, AES-NI
yukti    — Device abstraction (USB, optical, block, GPU via /sys/class/drm, network, udev)
mabda    — GPU foundation via wgpu-native C shim
sankoch  — Lossless compression (LZ4, DEFLATE, zlib, gzip)

USAGE PATTERN:
    include "lib/alloc.cyr"
    include "lib/vec.cyr"
    alloc_init();
    var v = vec_new();
    vec_push(v, 42);

INCLUDE ORDER FOR FULL STACK (dependency-safe):
    include "lib/string.cyr"
    include "lib/fmt.cyr"
    include "lib/alloc.cyr"
    include "lib/vec.cyr"
    include "lib/str.cyr"
    include "lib/tagged.cyr"
    include "lib/syscalls.cyr"
    include "lib/io.cyr"
    include "lib/hashmap.cyr"
    include "lib/process.cyr"
    include "lib/fs.cyr"

IMPORTANT — `var buf[N]` allocates N BYTES, not N elements:
    var buf[120];     # 120 bytes (enough for sysinfo struct)
    var uts[392];     # 392 bytes (enough for utsname struct: 6 × 65 + padding)
    store64(&buf, 42);          # write 8 bytes at offset 0
    store64(&buf + 8, 43);      # write 8 bytes at offset 8
